-- Hankook, KT, Perisai, Petronas, Wesfarmers: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview
-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 2010-12-22T21:10:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-22/hankook-kt-perisai-petronas-wesfarmers-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in  Asian trading , excluding Japan.
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  BES Engineering Corp.  (2515 TT): The Taiwanese engineering
and construction company won a bid for a construction project at
the National United University for NT$388 million ($13 million),
it said in a statement to the stock exchange. BES slipped 0.6
percent to NT$9.01.  China Minsheng Banking Corp.  (600016 CH): The lender won a
bid to buy a piece of land in the business district of Beijing
for 3 billion yuan ($451 million), according to a statement on
the Hong Kong’s stock exchange. Minsheng dropped 1.2 percent to
5.06 yuan.  Hankook Tire Co.  (000240 KS): South Korea’s biggest
tiremaker will invest $353 million to build a new plant in
Indonesia, the company said in a regulatory filing. The company
expects production at the plant to begin in November 2012, it
said. Hankook climbed 0.5 percent to 33,850 won.       Petaling Tin Bhd.  (PEG MK): The Malaysian property
developer said profit in the fourth quarter ended Oct. 31 rose
to 2.41 million ringgit ($770,000) from 850,000 ringgit a year
earlier after sales increased. Petaling Tin fell 1.4 percent to
35.5 sen.  CJ CheilJedang Corp.  (097950 KS): South Korea’s largest
food processor denied a JoongAng Ilbo report that it plans to
buy a Brazilian sugar-processing company. The South Korean food
company made the comment in a regulatory filing. The stock
gained 2.1 percent to 217,000 won.  KT Corp.  (030200 KS): South Korea’s largest phone and
Internet company registered to sell as much as 100 billion yen
($1.2 billion) of Samurai bonds, according to a filing with
Japan’s finance ministry. The registration takes effect on Jan.
5 and is valid for two years. KT fell 0.1 percent to 47,950 won.       Perisai Petroleum Teknologi Bhd.  (PPT MK): Mercury Pacific
Marine Pte. sold 1 million shares in Perisai, trimming its stake
in the Malaysian oil and gas services provider to 24.2 percent,
a stock-exchange filing showed. Perisai declined 2.5 percent to
58 sen.       Petronas Chemicals Bhd.  (PCHEM MK): The Employees Provident
Fund, Malaysia’s biggest pension fund, bought 9.4 million shares
in the petrochemicals company, boosting its stake to 7.48
percent, a stock-exchange filing showed. Petronas Chemicals rose
0.4 percent to 5.57 ringgit.  Uni-President Enterprises Corp.  (1216 TT): Taiwan’s largest
food processor will build a beverage production line in the
northwestern Chinese province of Gansu with a total investment
of $36 million, the Xinhua News Agency reported, citing local
authorities. Uni-President fell 0.1 percent to NT$42.90.  Wesfarmers Ltd.  (WES AU): The Australian company with
businesses ranging from coal mines to home-improvement stores
has executed a A$2.5 billion ($2.5 billion) revolving facility
agreement. The facility comprises two A$1.25 billion tranches
with a three-year tranche maturing in December 2013 and a four-
year tranche maturing in December 2014. Wesfarmers advanced 0.5
percent to A$32.18.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Berni Moestafa  in Jakarta at 
